address = {New York, NY, USA},
url = {https://doi.org/10.1145/1978942.1979225},
doi = {10.1145/1978942.1979225},
abstract = {Providing firefighters working on the frontline of interventions with ubiquitous computing
support remains an open challenge. Designing meaningful solutions for this complex
work environment requires reflective thought and conceptual understanding of its social
configuration. This paper presents organizing patterns of firefighting frontline practice
as a means to inform ubiquitous computing design processes. The patterns originate
from a qualitative analysis of an extensive range of user studies conducted with French
and German firefighters. As the patterns show, firefighting on the frontline is based
on a rigid structure that gains its flexibility through independent units whose safety
is ensured by a number of monitoring activities. We conclude that the interaction
between the presented patterns forms a balanced whole and needs to be recognized by
ubiquitous computing design.},
