has been primarily inspired by behavior change models that best fit individual change,
less attention has been deserved to test their validity in the context of collective
behavior change, where interdependencies between people's choices and behaviors matter,
as in the shared use of limited resources or public goods. We discuss some relevant
directions to fill this gap, based on the iterative design of BeeParking, a feedback
display aimed to induce more cooperative use of a parking facility within a work environment.},
booktitle = {Proceedings of the SIGCHI Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems},
