abstract = {Despite being an important channel for end-user assistance, few studies have directly
investigated the interactions that occur in modern-day practice of software product
support. We present results from a multi-dimensional analysis of product support activities
at a leading design software company. We carried out a quantitative analysis of existing
support requests, a survey with product support specialists, and follow-up interviews
to understand the current practices in product support. In particular, we investigated
the utility of different multimedia formats that modern web-based support systems
enable. Our results showed that despite the value that these formats bring to support
tasks, support specialists still face bottlenecks in remotely resolving software problems.
We conclude by highlighting several opportunities in HCI for improving diagnosis and
resolution of software issues over the web.},
